tradition, and repressive sexual mores. They founded organizations and periodicals, circulated brochures, and hosted lectures and conferences, all aimed at rethinking ethics for a secular modernity. Arising in a context sharply influenced by materialism, Darwinism, and the advent of sexology, ethics debates gradually focused not surprisingly on the role of sexuality in definitions of ethics and of the moral subject. Intellectuals and activists came to agree that sexuality was central to the formation of the moral subject. Some viewed the moral subject as that individual who had learned to suppress sexual drives, while others saw sexual drives and sexual autonomy as the source of moral energy and sentiment. The association of sexuality with a wide and variegated discussion of ethics made the sexualized moral subject an open concept that could not be fully regulated, confined, or conflated with national identities. Matysik's compelling intellectual and cultural history of ethics and moral subjectivity reframes the nature of German liberalism and intellectual activism from the end of the nineteenth century until the interwar period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEthical culture movementzEurope, CentralxHistoryy19th century. 0aEthical culture movementzEurope, CentralxHistoryy20th century. 0aSexual ethicszEurope, CentralxHistoryy19th century. 0aSexual ethicszEurope, CentralxHistoryy20th century. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172443540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501724435423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501724435/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000